1
00:00:02,123 --> 00:00:16,989
Foundation Course 1, Talk 9, The Fourth Noble Truth, Right Understanding So we come full circle, back to the problem of wisdom, which in Buddhist terms means the solution to the problem of suffering.

2
00:00:18,332 --> 00:00:26,004
If the Buddha had less just a philosophy or psychology, he would no doubt be considered these days to be one of the greatest thinkers of mankind.

3
00:00:26,591 --> 00:00:39,064
But what sets the Buddha apart from philosophers was that he also left a methodology, a systematic practice whereby each and every individual could make their own discovery of what he himself had discovered.

4
00:00:41,927 --> 00:00:44,750
The fourth noble truth is the Noble Eightfold Path.

5
00:00:45,853 --> 00:00:53,780
It is divided into three sections, morality, mental development and wisdom, and it contains this practice, this methodology.

6
00:00:54,756 --> 00:00:57,783
Wisdom is what is gained in terms of our personal experience.

7
00:00:59,104 --> 00:01:07,221
These guidelines, called by the Buddha from his own experiential wisdom, act as guidelines directing the whole process of self-enlightenment.

8
00:01:08,703 --> 00:01:15,296
There is the wisdom we gain through insight and the wisdom we gain through compassionate action or ordinary daily experience.

9
00:01:16,340 --> 00:01:26,215
Both of these are supported by what we learn from other sources, such as books, magazines, TV, and of course people, and by how we ourselves think.

10
00:01:28,218 --> 00:01:33,688
I'm sure everyone has had the experience of buying a do-it-yourself furniture kit, a sort of adult Lego.

11
00:01:35,189 --> 00:01:36,912
If you're like me, you take everything out.

12
00:01:37,213 --> 00:01:46,162
Quickly work out in your head how it's supposed to go together and start fixing it up, only to come to the end of the labour to find one metal bracket or something left over.

13
00:01:47,302 --> 00:01:50,665
Because of this missing piece, the whole construction keeps falling over.

14
00:01:51,706 --> 00:01:58,091
So it all has to be dismantled and started again, only this time with a humbling and grudging read of the instructions.

15
00:01:59,813 --> 00:02:06,579
Others who do not suffer from such overweening self-confidence will carefully read the instructions or get a friend to instruct,

16
00:02:07,200 --> 00:02:14,031
Some, of course, will get a friend to do it, so that although they say they know how to do it, they haven't actually done it themselves.

17
00:02:15,774 --> 00:02:20,981
In all these cases, one or more of the above types of understanding has been employed.

18
00:02:22,084 --> 00:02:35,283
But the Buddha would have us tackle even such mundane things as building a DIY stool by first of all reading the instructions, then thinking about it, so we've actually understood it for ourselves, and then construct it.

19
00:02:36,614 --> 00:02:40,860
In this way, we can say we truly know what it means to construct a DIY stool.

20
00:02:42,382 --> 00:02:43,864
Now we're in a position to help others.

21
00:02:45,086 --> 00:02:49,812
I'm sure everyone has a friend who can fix things, and it ends up costing twice the professional fees.

22
00:02:51,335 --> 00:02:59,787
We can say that knowledge and wisdom is the more profound and authentic to the individual, the more it is discovered and experienced by that individual.

23
00:03:02,634 --> 00:03:07,843
So it's the same sort of attitude the Buddha wants us to apply to his teaching.

24
00:03:08,786 --> 00:03:16,460
When he explains to me that there is no lasting entity or soul to be found in the body and mind, I understand it, but I'm not convinced.

25
00:03:17,360 --> 00:03:23,412
Then I go away and ponder over it and check it out with my own logic, arguing with other beliefs I have within myself.

26
00:03:24,639 --> 00:03:30,326
If after all my thinking I understand it to be right, then it becomes almost my own argument, as it were.

27
00:03:31,048 --> 00:03:32,750
But as yet, it's all head stuff.

28
00:03:33,651 --> 00:03:38,016
I have not actually experienced the insubstantiality of my body and mind.

29
00:03:39,378 --> 00:03:46,587
Scientists, for instance, tell us there is no difference between my body and the plaster on the walls in terms of subatomic particles.

30
00:03:47,368 --> 00:03:50,513
But I don't experience myself as subatomic activity.

31
00:03:51,420 --> 00:03:56,467
Through the meditation practice, I can experience the teaching of insubstantiality.

32
00:03:57,568 --> 00:04:01,814
I do begin to experience for myself the insubstantial nature of my body and mind.

33
00:04:02,616 --> 00:04:07,102
And when this happens, my knowledge is the wisdom of seeing things as they really are.

34
00:04:08,143 --> 00:04:09,384
Experiential knowledge.

35
00:04:10,286 --> 00:04:13,670
This is realization, to realize the truth.

36
00:04:14,611 --> 00:04:17,495
According to the Buddha, this is the only true wisdom.

37
00:04:19,754 --> 00:04:23,800
Herein lies the importance of different types of wisdom in Buddhist practice.

38
00:04:24,480 --> 00:04:34,216
The progression from received knowledge to one's own personal conclusions to realization through actual experience is expressed by the Buddha like this.

39
00:04:35,416 --> 00:04:43,769
There are two conditions to the arising of right understanding, namely instruction by another and one's own wise consideration.

40
00:04:46,197 --> 00:04:49,824
The importance of right understanding is that it is the first step.

41
00:04:50,283 --> 00:04:53,370
If our first step is wrong, we may very well get lost.

42
00:04:54,773 --> 00:04:56,675
The Buddha says it in a more poetic way.

43
00:04:57,737 --> 00:05:10,281
Just as the red morning sky is the forerunner and first indication of the rising of the sun, just so is right understanding the forerunner and first indication of karmically wholesome things.

44
00:05:12,725 --> 00:05:18,252
So here expressed very clearly is the link between right understanding, karma, and our destiny.

45
00:05:19,374 --> 00:05:22,639
Before we make any decision, we do it by way of understanding.

46
00:05:23,880 --> 00:05:30,250
If I'm going to buy one of these DIY kits, I'd be very foolish if I didn't understand what it entails.

47
00:05:31,310 --> 00:05:36,218
Once I understand, my decisions put ideas into force, into action.

48
00:05:37,125 --> 00:05:42,274
Right intention, the second part of the wisdom division of this Noble Eightfold Path, is just that.

49
00:05:43,036 --> 00:05:50,088
It is the will putting force into ideas, plans, projects, which run along the lines laid down by right understanding.

50
00:05:51,752 --> 00:05:56,581
Having understood the meditation, what the actual practice and theory is, I then decide to sit.

51
00:05:57,122 --> 00:05:59,286
This decision is right intention.

52
00:06:01,425 --> 00:06:06,550
Right understanding undercuts delusion, whereas right intention undercuts greed and hatred.

53
00:06:07,271 --> 00:06:13,598
In this way, right understanding and right intention destroy the roots of all unwholesome karma, of all suffering.

54
00:06:15,259 --> 00:06:19,744
We will never intend to keep the three primary precepts or the five training rules.

55
00:06:20,504 --> 00:06:23,668
We will never intend to practice the perfections.

56
00:06:24,327 --> 00:06:29,273
We will never intend to meditate if we have no knowledge or understanding of them.

57
00:06:30,315 --> 00:06:34,942
Right understanding is the foundation of the middle path, the path of purification.

58
00:06:36,805 --> 00:06:38,346
So what is right understanding?

59
00:06:40,028 --> 00:06:48,319
It is of course enshrined in the Four Noble Truths which were succinctly expressed in the Buddha's first talk, the Discourse on the Turning of the Wheel of the Law.

60
00:06:50,663 --> 00:06:57,252
Here the first distinction that he made is what should be avoided by one who has gone forth from the worldly life.

61
00:06:58,024 --> 00:07:03,132
This doesn't just refer to monks and nuns, but to anyone who is turning towards a spiritual dimension.

62
00:07:04,252 --> 00:07:05,173
There are three paths.

63
00:07:05,956 --> 00:07:10,822
The path of sensual pleasure, the path of self-mortification, and the middle path.

64
00:07:12,283 --> 00:07:17,050
The whole of the Buddha's teachings can be seen as a destruction of sensual desire.

65
00:07:18,372 --> 00:07:21,415
Remember, this doesn't mean there's no tastiness to our food anymore.

66
00:07:21,956 --> 00:07:23,077
It means the end of greed.

67
00:07:23,899 --> 00:07:27,423
To end greed, we also need to end its twin, hatred.

68
00:07:28,720 --> 00:07:35,887
Self-mortification, thinking that the body and mind are bad and evil and must somehow be destroyed, is wrong understanding.

69
00:07:36,829 --> 00:07:38,149
There is nothing evil in nature.

70
00:07:38,790 --> 00:07:40,512
Nature is perfect just as it is.

71
00:07:41,254 --> 00:07:50,983
It is our view of things that causes suffering, and there is no escape in self-hatred or repression or by means of self-mortification, such as long fasts and so on.

72
00:07:52,105 --> 00:07:58,052
The middle path is simply to understand the crucial point that our greed and hatred are the roots of our misery.

73
00:07:59,163 --> 00:08:03,127
Once we've understood that, we have gone a long way to destroying our delusions.

74
00:08:04,089 --> 00:08:05,110
Our wisdom is growing.

75
00:08:06,773 --> 00:08:11,178
Over Christmas and New Year, for instance, everyone drinks and eats so much, we get fat.

76
00:08:12,221 --> 00:08:13,882
That's the path of personal pleasure.

77
00:08:15,185 --> 00:08:17,848
Afterwards, we worry about cholesterol and heart attacks.

78
00:08:18,309 --> 00:08:21,473
We suffer ourselves to eat less and cut out what we like.

79
00:08:22,093 --> 00:08:23,696
That's the path of mortification.

80
00:08:24,776 --> 00:08:28,882
The middle path is to eat when we are hungry and until the body has had enough.

81
00:08:30,043 --> 00:08:43,842
The middle path is hedged, both by the thorny bush of model laws which safeguard us from doing anything unwholesome, unskillful or harmful, and the flowering bushes of the perfections that perfume and beautify our journey.

82
00:08:44,924 --> 00:08:49,650
The path itself is our steps, our actions, what we do and how we do.

83
00:08:50,653 --> 00:08:57,182
It is the meditative life in which sitting meditation trains us to live in action in a mindful and careful way.

84
00:08:59,692 --> 00:09:08,206
In the second of the Buddha's talks, given to the same five monks, he is concerned to extend their understanding of the underlying characteristics of human nature.

85
00:09:09,489 --> 00:09:12,794
Delusion causes us to identify with our pleasures.

86
00:09:13,436 --> 00:09:14,658
We think that's what we are.

87
00:09:15,138 --> 00:09:16,801
We think that's what life is about.

88
00:09:17,863 --> 00:09:22,691
This delusion is the theory upon which our greeds and hatreds are founded.

89
00:09:23,932 --> 00:09:25,836
To understand the nature of our delusion,

90
00:09:26,068 --> 00:09:35,078
is paramount if we are going to achieve the right understanding without which all our intentions and all our actions will be leading us towards suffering, not away from it.

91
00:09:36,900 --> 00:09:38,863
The Buddha converses with his disciples.

92
00:09:40,443 --> 00:09:41,144
What do you think?

93
00:09:41,225 --> 00:09:42,947
Is the body permanent or impermanent?

94
00:09:43,628 --> 00:09:44,427
Impermanent, Lord.

95
00:09:45,269 --> 00:09:48,432
And is this impermanence something that brings happiness or unhappiness?

96
00:09:49,214 --> 00:09:50,575
Unhappiness, Lord.

97
00:09:50,774 --> 00:09:57,746
And is it right to understand what is impermanent and what destroys happiness as mine, me or myself?

98
00:09:58,368 --> 00:09:58,828
No, Lord.

99
00:10:00,211 --> 00:10:05,380
So he questions them concerning the whole mind, its feelings, thoughts, emotions and even consciousness.

100
00:10:07,164 --> 00:10:08,386
All are not permanent.

101
00:10:09,067 --> 00:10:14,317
Do not bring happiness and do not constitute a me or soul or a self.

102
00:10:15,900 --> 00:10:43,326
If we really understand this, that there is nothing in our body and minds that we can hold on to, since it is all arising and passing away, if we really understand that we can't call any of it a permanent me or ego or soul or self, then, says the Buddha, understanding this, a wise noble disciple loses his passion for things of the body, his passion for feelings, for thoughts, for emotions, for consciousness.

103
00:10:43,998 --> 00:10:48,403
When he loses the passion for these things, his greeds and obsessions fade away.

104
00:10:49,384 --> 00:10:52,847
When greeds and obsessions fade away, the heart is liberated.

105
00:10:53,727 --> 00:10:58,013
When the heart is liberated, then he comes to know this is liberation.

106
00:10:58,813 --> 00:11:01,297
He understands this is the end of birth.

107
00:11:01,797 --> 00:11:03,418
The holy life has been completed.

108
00:11:04,299 --> 00:11:06,501
What needed to be done has been done.

109
00:11:07,143 --> 00:11:09,144
There is no more rebirth for me.

110
00:11:10,659 --> 00:11:14,524
Please notice, the heart is not lost with the destruction of desire.

111
00:11:15,083 --> 00:11:16,085
It is liberated.

112
00:11:18,726 --> 00:11:27,375
This talk was so clear to the five disciples that they were all totally liberated as their new understanding coupled with their meditation practice came to fruition.

113
00:11:28,235 --> 00:11:30,557
There and then they were released from their delusions.

114
00:11:31,860 --> 00:11:37,764
Becoming more and more aware of the changing nature of our lives will always undermine our attachment to it.

115
00:11:38,182 --> 00:11:41,067
When someone dear to us dies, it is extremely painful.

116
00:11:42,107 --> 00:11:46,594
Yet if the mourning process is successful, most of our sorrow will have passed within a year.

117
00:11:47,514 --> 00:11:50,799
Within five or ten years, there may not even be a sad memory.

118
00:11:51,660 --> 00:11:54,904
Instead, we will remember the person with warmth, joy and gratitude.

119
00:11:56,147 --> 00:11:59,591
Virtually all suffering caused by that separation will disappear.

120
00:12:00,773 --> 00:12:02,115
This is what the Buddha taught.

121
00:12:03,006 --> 00:12:08,355
If we can accept that life is impermanent and uncertain, our attachment to it will be questioned.

122
00:12:09,456 --> 00:12:13,422
As we come to see that life is forever on the move, we won't hold on to anything.

123
00:12:14,082 --> 00:12:17,006
We expect things to change, be it for the better or the worse.

124
00:12:17,327 --> 00:12:18,408
It doesn't matter anymore.

125
00:12:19,591 --> 00:12:23,076
What matters is how we react to it, how we are affected by it.

126
00:12:24,158 --> 00:12:29,264
It is of no use to our dead loved ones if we spend the rest of our lives in misery at their passing away.

127
00:12:30,025 --> 00:12:31,207
It's hardly what they'd want.

128
00:12:31,677 --> 00:12:33,379
They'd want us to get on with living.

129
00:12:34,140 --> 00:12:35,202
That's what the Buddha taught.

130
00:12:35,703 --> 00:12:36,885
Don't hold on to life.

131
00:12:37,547 --> 00:12:39,490
Just get on with living here and now.

132
00:12:40,392 --> 00:12:43,298
But with right understanding and right intention, of course.

133
00:12:46,062 --> 00:12:51,491
The path that Buddhists follow, the middle path, also contains different levels of commitment and insight.

134
00:12:52,129 --> 00:12:56,496
A person who experiences Nibbana is known as a Sotapanna or stream entrant.

135
00:12:57,357 --> 00:13:02,466
It is said of a Sotapanna that her or his faith in the Buddha Dharma Sangha is unshakable.

136
00:13:03,447 --> 00:13:08,173
For now they know by their own experience the third noble truth, the end of suffering.

137
00:13:09,436 --> 00:13:11,919
Unfortunately, however, this is not the end of training.

138
00:13:12,681 --> 00:13:18,389
Even though total liberation to such a person is assured, there are three further noble paths to be obtained.

139
00:13:19,349 --> 00:13:25,498
The second is called sakadagami, and at this stage the bonds of attachment and hatred are only loosened.

140
00:13:26,479 --> 00:13:33,769
It is only on achieving the third path, anagami, that these bonds that tie us to sensual pleasures are finally cut.

141
00:13:34,630 --> 00:13:36,913
Even so, the training must still go on.

142
00:13:37,855 --> 00:13:43,462
Final liberation is achieved when the attainment of the arahat, which literally means to have killed all enemies.

143
00:13:43,903 --> 00:13:46,167
The enemies, of course, are greed, hatred and delusion.

144
00:13:47,243 --> 00:13:51,328
These four types of persons are known as the noble community, Arya Sangha.

145
00:13:51,970 --> 00:13:53,032
They are the Buddhist saints.

146
00:13:54,514 --> 00:14:06,452
When a Buddhist bows three times towards a shrine, he's taking refuge in the Buddha, the historical personage, and the enlightenment, the Dharma, the doctrine, and the Sangha, this community of saints.

147
00:14:07,735 --> 00:14:13,182
Taking refuge means to put one's trust in the triple gem, or the three jewels, as they are often called.

148
00:14:14,176 --> 00:14:20,466
This act of refuge, plus the taking of the five training rules, is how a person becomes a Buddhist.

149
00:14:20,485 --> 00:14:30,160
But the formula is repeated by devout Buddhists every day, and it is common to make a special effort every quarter moon, approximately once a week.

150
00:14:30,181 --> 00:14:34,187
These four days, per lunar month, are known as Upasatha days.

151
00:14:34,927 --> 00:14:42,899
Lay people often go to the monastery on these days to meditate, or just to spend a quiet, reflective day within monastic grounds.

152
00:14:44,062 --> 00:14:56,216
For those who have not attained one of the paths, there is an understanding that if certain teachings are truly understood, development towards the first aryan path, sotapanna, the stream entrant to intuit nibbana, is assured.

153
00:14:57,577 --> 00:15:01,403
That teaching is called the light of the analytical knowledge of causation.

154
00:15:02,624 --> 00:15:06,349
There are three types of wrong understanding concerning the law of causation.

155
00:15:06,969 --> 00:15:09,192
The law of cause and effect, the law of karma.

156
00:15:10,149 --> 00:15:17,182
The first is to say that existence, life, what we do, what happens to us, arises without a cause.

157
00:15:18,245 --> 00:15:22,793
Right understanding states that everything happens because of something else.

158
00:15:23,634 --> 00:15:24,657
Everything is caused.

159
00:15:25,177 --> 00:15:27,282
Everything is the effect of a cause.

160
00:15:29,152 --> 00:15:35,640
The second is to say that existence, life, what we do, what happens to us, arises spontaneously or because of some deity.

161
00:15:36,461 --> 00:15:38,365
This is also wrong understanding.

162
00:15:38,905 --> 00:15:41,730
Every birth and action is conditioned by past actions.

163
00:15:43,312 --> 00:15:49,801
Thirdly, to say that only past actions condition the present and future is not right understanding either.

164
00:15:50,702 --> 00:15:54,567
To believe this would be to believe in predestination, in sealed fate.

165
00:15:55,222 --> 00:16:01,750
In reality, the present moment and the future are also affected by our present decisions now.

166
00:16:03,173 --> 00:16:07,839
If this were not possible, we would not be able to affect any change within ourselves.

167
00:16:09,341 --> 00:16:21,635
If we would simply be doomed by fate, it is knowing that we can take certain control, especially of our decision-making, that makes the whole process of purification and eventual liberation possible.

168
00:16:23,826 --> 00:16:31,437
In other words, to have truly understood the law of karma is to have the light which will lead meditators out of the dark.

169
00:16:32,499 --> 00:16:44,575
The Buddha talked of four kinds of persons, those going from dark to dark, from light to dark, the unfortunates, and those going from dark to light, and from light to light, the fortunates.

170
00:16:45,876 --> 00:16:50,543
Understanding that we can be in control of this process through our will,

171
00:16:50,894 --> 00:16:54,321
means we have the ability to start moving in the right way.

172
00:16:55,462 --> 00:17:05,321
Understanding that unwholesome thoughts, words and actions produce the same, and that wholesome thoughts, words and actions produce the same, means we can now see the light.

173
00:17:06,824 --> 00:17:13,897
At least, at this level, we're beginning to see the connection between what we think, say and do, and what happens to us.

174
00:17:15,413 --> 00:17:23,746
Even if the outer consequences of our actions are not immediately obvious, by our meditative practice we come to know their immediate effect on the mind and heart.

175
00:17:25,028 --> 00:17:28,093
If I'm angry with someone, maybe he'll try and get his own back.

176
00:17:28,794 --> 00:17:29,894
Of that I'm not sure.

177
00:17:30,596 --> 00:17:32,558
I don't know what the outer effect will be.

178
00:17:33,160 --> 00:17:40,711
But when I meditate and see how this anger affects me and myself, then at least I'm aware of its negative and unhealthy effects on me.

179
00:17:41,941 --> 00:17:46,828
I notice the effects are quite the opposite if I'm kind and gentle and helpful.

180
00:17:48,310 --> 00:17:52,858
Slowly, this analytical knowledge of causation begins to be our guiding light.

181
00:17:54,221 --> 00:17:58,346
Then we can say such a person is a chula sattvapanna, a lesser stream entrant.

182
00:17:59,829 --> 00:18:04,336
We can be sure that such a person will try to develop the perfections and practice meditation.

183
00:18:05,481 --> 00:18:13,512
The later commentaries on the scriptures assure us that such a person will not end up in situations where his training will not be able to continue.

184
00:18:14,134 --> 00:18:19,362
In other words, his mentality and actions will lead to situations conducive to training.

185
00:18:21,825 --> 00:18:25,471
To guide such a person, the Buddha clearly laid out the Noble Eightfold Path.

186
00:18:26,251 --> 00:18:32,079
By following this, especially the Sila – right action, right speech and right livelihood –

187
00:18:32,161 --> 00:18:36,204
The fourth type of wisdom arises, wisdom in action, compassion.

188
00:18:37,267 --> 00:18:42,592
For this is also the aim of any meditation, to help other fellow beings towards the enlightenment.

189
00:18:43,794 --> 00:18:49,138
This doesn't mean to preach Buddhism, it means to help others in whatever capacity a person feels able.

190
00:18:50,039 --> 00:18:59,990
To guide a child in moral understanding, to feed a sick person and comfort them with encouraging words, to listen to the problems of some friend or colleague, to give to good causes,

191
00:19:00,307 --> 00:19:03,394
Whatever is compassionate is to practice the perfections.

192
00:19:04,777 --> 00:19:05,818
It's a two-way stream.

193
00:19:06,319 --> 00:19:12,571
Learning to be patient with the angry child is to learn to be patient with our own internal worrying childish thoughts.

194
00:19:13,753 --> 00:19:19,285
Learning how to care for and comfort ourselves is to learn how to care for and comfort others.

195
00:19:21,108 --> 00:19:21,809
So this is it.

196
00:19:22,329 --> 00:19:33,722
This is all the Buddha would have us do, to study ourselves, our lives, to make the connections, to decide to follow what is wise, to cease from harm, to do good, to purify the mind.

197
00:19:34,443 --> 00:19:35,925
This is the teaching of all the Buddhas.

198
00:19:37,106 --> 00:19:39,769
Like most things, easy to say, hard to do.

199
00:19:40,691 --> 00:19:43,753
But it's worth the effort, for the fruits of our labour are sweet.

200
00:19:44,996 --> 00:19:51,222
The middle path really does bring peace, joy, love and harmony, and in the end, liberation.

201
00:19:51,962 --> 00:19:53,263
